@flexiarg forward-model/price-your-own-moves
@title Price Your Own Moves
@sigils [⟡/?]
@audience futon stack operators, agents, forward-model authors
@tone conjectural
@style pattern

! conclusion: A self-model that recommends its own next move must rank moves by realized value, uptake, reward, market, not only by its internally-argued expected value.

  + context: Forward-model hypothesis, not yet attested. Extends the attested ruling that the next-move surface is the recursive closure.

  + IF:
    The stack has a live next-move surface that ranks candidate moves by the self-model's own expected-free-energy or internal argument.

  + HOWEVER:
    An internally-argued ranking can be self-confirming: the model rewards the moves it already believes in, with no outside signal that a move actually paid.

  + THEN:
    Bind each recommended move to a realized-value signal from outside the model, operator uptake, learned reward, or market outcome, and let that signal reprice the ranking. A move's expected value stays provisional until an external outcome confirms it.

  + BECAUSE:
    Self-representation without a price becomes the hermit failure, arguing beautifully for moves nobody needed. Pricing moves by realized value is the economic completion of the recursive closure: the loop closes on the world, not just on itself.

    + evidence: Bridge target, not yet attested. Would connect the next-move surface to the interim-director livelihood model and the mission-conditional reward line in the backlog cascade.
